english: The land where Rana Pratap fought for freedom.
banjara: Rana Pratap eez jammi par aazadier vasu ladai karmeloch
notes: katth-where, Rana Pratap-Rana Pratap, eez-this only, jammi par- on land, aazadier-of freedom, vasu-for, ladai-fight karmeloch-have done

english: We, the Banjaras—also called Lambadis and Gor—belonged to Rajput clans.
banjara: banjara, lambadi, gor kajon aapen shee rajput cha
notes: hum-we, balayo-called, anne-and, een-to, banjara-banjara, lambadi-banjara, gor-banjara, kajon-saidso/meant, aapen-us, shee-all, rajput cha-are rajputs

english: Specifically, the Rathod clan of Chittorgarh.
banjara: seeti aang rathod kajakon chittorgarh eethi aamech
notes: eer-of chittorgarh, seeti-all, aang-before, rathod-rathod, kajakon-to be ssaid so, meant to be, chittorgarh-chittorgarh, eethi-from, aamech-came

english: Our ancestors were not merely traders.
banjara: apan shee pena jaag jaag pharthaneen vyapaar ekkaaj koni karmele
notes: aapner-our, apan-we, shee-all, pena-ancient/old days, jaag jaag-place to place, pharthaneen-roaming around, vyapaar-business/trading, ekkaaj-only one, koni-not, karmele-have done

english: We were the logistics backbone of Rajput armies.
banjara: apan rajput sena vur saaman punchadeen mooreer hadkar nai vette
notes: hum-we, eevur-of, apan-we, rajput sena vur -rajput army's, saaman-logistics/goods, punchadeen-to reach/available, mooreer hadkar - backbone, nai-like, vette-were there.

english: We supplied provisions to Prithviraj Chauhan's forces.
banjara: apan, prithviraj chauhan eer senaan bhi kai chavtoi deethethe
notes: hum-we, een-to, apan-we/us, prithviraj chauhan eer-prithviraj chauhan's, senaan-army/forces, bhi-also, kai chavtoi-what ever is needed/ what ever is wanted, deethethe-used to give.

english: We transported grain and weapons for Rana Pratap.
banjara: apan rana prathap eer vasu daana an hatiyaar leen jaathe the
notes: hum-we, anne-and, apan-we, rana prathap eer-rana prathap's, vasu-for, daana-grains, an-and, hatiyaar-weapons, leen-take/took and, jaathe the- used to go

english: We crossed mountains and rivers with our bullock caravans.
banjara: apan baladure bandi bhaandleen katraiko pahad gatla an nadhivun paar karmelecha
notes: hum-we, anne-and, aapner-our, apan-we, baladure-bull's, bandi-bullock cart/cart, bhaandleen-tying/tied, katraiko-soo many, pahad-mountains, gatla-hills, an-and, nadhivun-rivers, paar-cross, karmelecha-did/done.
hum-we, anne-and, apan-we, vyapaare-traders/businessman, anne-and, yoddha-warriors, vetthe-were there.

banjara: peena thi eez apneer pehechan che
notes: peena thi - from ancient times, eez-this, apneer-our, pehechan che- is identity
